sed
sed 's/old/new/' filename : replace old word to new word. one word in one line
   sed 's/old/new/g' filename : make changes entirely in every line even if contains same old word
  sed -i 's/old/new/g' filename : save the changes after changing the old word to new
   sed -n 5,10p filename : gives those lines in between 5 and 10 and p = print
   sed '3d' filename : deletes only line number 3
   sed '2,10d' filename : deletes lines from 2 to 10
   sed '/hello/d' bigdata.txt : Deletes lines containing hello
   sed '/hi/i\hello' bigdata.txt : adds hello in line before hi word in file
   sed '/hi/a\hello' bigdata.txt : adds hello after line of hi
   sed 's/emp/employee/g' bigdata.txt > output.txt : Output goes to output.txt,If output.txt already exists it is overwritten
   sed 's/emp/employee/g' bigdata.txt >> output.txt : It does NOT erase existing content, It adds new output at bottom

